aboutSections.name: About
aboutSections.description: This is a salsa you've probably never heard about. The closest thing is the famous chili crisp, such as the Chinese Lao Gan Ma. Salsa Matcha is a concoction of dried chiles, nuts, seeds fried in oil, blended, and hit with a touch of vinegar to brighten things up. It can be used over anything! This recipe is based on very common ones, with a touch of chile morita (chipotle morita) to add the most amazing smokiness.

aboutSections.name: Oil, Chiles, Nuts, Seeds
aboutSections.description: You can use many different chiles, such as guajillo, puya, ancho, pasilla, arbol, chiptole. You can also use different nuts and seeds such as pumpkin seeds, peanuts, sesame seeds, maybe even pecans or almonds. This being said, it is very common to use just chile de arbol and peanuts. For oil, I prefer extra virgin olive oil because of its beautiful taste, but it is very common to see vegetable or corn oil. Lard is not used because it is not liquid at room temp, but something like fresh rendered pork lard would probably take this to another level.

steps.description: Add the oil and garlic to a pot over medium low, slowly cook the garlic until it is golden brown and soft. When done, leave the garlic in a blender
Toast the chiles in that same oil for about 2 minutes, stirring often, uintil the chiles change color. When done, leave ther chiles in the blender
Toast the peanuts and sesame seeds in that same oil for about 2 minutes, stirring often, uintil the chiles change color. When done, leave the peanuts and sesame seeds in the blender
With all the ingredients toasted and now in the blender, add the remaining oil (please make sure it isn't scorching hot and melt your blender!), vinegar, and salt. Blend until completely smooth!
Store in a sealed jar and enjoy!
